        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Shipments Overview",
            Slug = "shipments-overview",
            Summary = "What shipments are, the shipment lifecycle, line items, and how shipments connect to sales orders and invoices.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/shipments"]""",
            Tags = """["shipments","shipping"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Shipments Overview\n\nThe Shipments module tracks every outbound shipment from your shop. Each shipment is tied to a Sales Order and contains one or more line items that describe what is being shipped, in what quantity. Shipments move through a defined lifecycle from creation to delivery, and they connect directly to invoicing so you always know what has been shipped and billed.\n\n### What Is a Shipment?\n\nA shipment represents a physical package or set of packages leaving your facility to fulfill (or partially fulfill) a Sales Order. Each shipment has:\n- A unique **Shipment Number** (auto-generated)\n- A link to exactly one **Sales Order**\n- One or more **Line Items** specifying parts and quantities\n- Optional **Carrier** and **Tracking Number** for logistics\n- Optional **Weight** and **Shipping Cost** for record-keeping\n- A **Status** indicating where the shipment is in its lifecycle\n\n### Shipment Lifecycle\n\nShipments follow a linear status progression:\n\n1. **Pending** — Shipment has been created but nothing has been packed yet. This is the initial status for all new shipments.\n2. **Packed** — Items have been physically packed and are ready to ship. The shipment is waiting for carrier pickup or drop-off.\n3. **Shipped** — The shipment has left your facility. The shipped date is recorded automatically when you mark it shipped.\n4. **In Transit** — The carrier has the shipment and it is en route to the customer. Tracking information updates are available if a tracking number is provided.\n5. **Delivered** — The shipment has been received by the customer. The delivered date is recorded automatically.\n6. **Cancelled** — The shipment was cancelled before delivery. Cancelled shipments are preserved for audit purposes.\n\nYou can move a shipment forward through statuses using the action buttons in the detail view. Shipments can be marked shipped from either Pending or Packed status, and marked delivered from either Shipped or In Transit status.\n\n### Line Items\n\nEach shipment line is created **from a line on the linked Sales Order** — you do not pick parts from a free part catalog. When you create a shipment, you select a Sales Order first, and the dialog then offers only that order's open lines. You pick a Sales Order Line and a quantity; the quantity is **capped at what remains to ship** on that line (the order can never be over-shipped). A single Sales Order can have multiple shipments (partial deliveries), and each shipment tracks exactly which order lines and quantities were included.\n\n### How Shipments Connect to Other Features\n\n**Sales Orders:** Every shipment belongs to one Sales Order. The Sales Order tracks overall fulfillment across all its shipments. You can see the linked Sales Order directly from the shipment detail view.\n\n**Invoices:** After a shipment is shipped, it can be linked to an Invoice. The shipment detail view shows the linked invoice when one exists, providing a clear audit trail from order to shipment to billing.\n\n**Customers:** The customer name and shipping address flow from the Sales Order. The shipment detail view shows the customer name and allows navigation to the Sales Order for full order context.\n\n**Carrier Integration:** The system supports carrier rate comparison and label generation. From the shipment detail, you can request shipping rates from configured carriers, compare options, and create a shipping label — all without leaving QB Engineer.\n\n**Tracking:** When a tracking number is entered (manually or via label creation), you can view the tracking timeline directly in the shipment detail. The timeline shows each tracking event with location, status, and timestamp.\n\n**Ship Document:** Once a shipment has a tracking number, the detail view exposes a **Download Ship Document** button (a versioned PDF that includes the shipment number, customer information, shipping address, and a table of all line items with quantities) plus a **Regenerate Ship Document** button to produce a fresh copy. Both buttons appear only after a tracking number exists. This is the document you print and include in the physical package.\n\n### When to Use Shipments\n\n- When fulfilling a Sales Order — create a shipment to record what is being sent\n- When shipping partial orders — create multiple shipments against the same Sales Order\n- When you need carrier rate comparison before choosing a shipping method\n- When you need tracking visibility for outbound packages\n- When downloading the ship document to include with shipments\n- When you need an audit trail connecting orders, shipments, and invoices","sections":[]}"""
        });

